Vaccination against pneumococci free and voluntary
Infection against pneumococci changes the habit from January.
It is said to be the first to be free and voluntary for families.
But voices are already making their voice heard that the mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococci culminate.
The Institute of Medicine already sets the maximum prices of vaccines that health insurance companies have to pay.
The experts are also aware of the vaccination procedure.
New vaccination
Vaccines free for August children
From January, children can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci born on 2 August last year and later.
The condition is that they have not received a dose of vaccine.
If you have already started vaccination in the past year or earlier, you will also have to pay for further vaccination yourself.
The first dose must be given between the 3rd and 5th months of life of the child.
A quarter of the families had their children vaccinated against pneumococci last year.
The parents paid 1600 kroner and more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest children requires four doses.
On the whole, the experts estimate that the health insurance funds spend 300,000 to 450,000 kroner per year on the doses.
However, they save on the treatment that children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all area vaccinations of children.
The mandatory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear infection, but also severe infections including brain inflammation and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections kill up to 28 children up to 10 years of age per year in hospitals.
Outside the Czech Republic, the compulsory vaccination of children against pneumococci was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
As of January, this is to be paid by insurance companies and voluntary.
For example, Rudolf Kalovsky, head of the Nahlas Citizens' Association, mentioned that the mandatory vaccination would be better.
His association has been promoting pneumococcal vaccination in the long term.
The experts at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very pleased with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
That's not exactly ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have succeeded in achieving at least that.
I think that's the way we need to go now, Kalovsky said.
The Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this moment, we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
The voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages, the doctors claim.
Hana Cabrnochova, chairman of the Association of Pediatricians, admits that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children had been vaccinated, one could think about the reduction in the number of re-vaccinations "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as a voluntary one," says Cabrnochova, however.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to have their infants vaccinated against pneumococci from next year.
Vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in that it is the first area vaccination to be paid by health insurance and not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend the money on prevention, thus saving them for further treatment, explains Cabrnochova.
The doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, this is linked to a concern of the practical pediatricians concerning the purchase of vaccines.
According to the original project, the vaccines should be bought by the insurance companies and the doctors should receive them in the same way as other vaccines issued by the state to them.
However, some MEPs feared that insurance could "carry out the money from health insurance" in this way.
That is why doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait until insurance companies pay them.
According to estimates, the individual practical doctors will have to invest 40,000 kroner per month, which is a significant sum.
It won't be easy, says Cabrnochova.
