Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, called "the big picture".
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which developed nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020 compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given the talks on Friday a boost through its commitment to provide US$3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from the mastery of floods and droughts to the prevention of deforestation.
