Some see pictures in a awake state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the mentally ill and in the drug rush the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are allowed to surrender ourselves uninhibited to the wildest imaginations and imaginations.
However, those who experience dreamlike conditions in wax, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicted in the modern Western world, at least as a special thing.
But such images and voices do not only come about in the case of mental illness or intoxication.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes make the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality blur.
Dream-like altered waking states can occur in different forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapture states, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the neuronal messenger substances of the brain - above all dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 that "a great similarity of delusion with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the inconsistencies, delusions, illusions of such."
It's autumn 2001 when Henning T. turns into a cartoon character.
His body is two-dimensional and squeaky-colored.
Gravity has no power over him, it's floating on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devil-figures with blood-red, distorted frays, squeaking teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar from walls and radio.
He can't stand them anymore, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables out of the stereo, knots them into a loop and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs on a speaker and lays the noose around his neck.
Jump.
The noose is loosening.
That's supposed to be a lesson to you, the voices scream in a drum-fur-shattering choir, "Go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last one is 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, he takes medications against depression, the mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness. He's been married for three years.
In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds; they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of size, relationship or persecution.
Voice listening is particularly common - voices that command, comment or dialog.
Even optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The affected person is no longer able to separate important things from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded by impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the floodgates for a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is in the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he, like in a dream, is overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A comparison of reality is usually not possible for them, the illusions are cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, is basically preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are rooted in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles still puzzles researchers.
Excess states can cause any human being to lose the reference to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that there are minimal brain damage in patients affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery, how the disorder of the neural system comes about, which at first does not manifest itself at all over many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says the Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether false images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a question of the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are one of the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of healthy people hallucinates.
According to Kasten, hallucinations are composed of memory contents that are normally held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is hot or when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But it's also the withdrawal of stimuli, stress, heartache or other mental states of exception.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents said they had experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the Gymnasium there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it wasn't for the pictures and the voices.
In the break it may happen that a limp boy with long, dark hair speaks to it.
When it answers, the classmates look at it surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions are not real and disappear again.
At night the apparitions are usually scary
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material, because the teacher presents a new student in her eyes and ears, while he explains mathematical equations for everyone else, both audible and visible, on the board.
At night the apparitions are usually scary.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which comes far too rarely and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees, the faces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes are created.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell her about it, they think they're crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed her Abitur last year and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations stopped a year ago.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art out of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from irritation, he is likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I guess the brain will be understaffed and will have its own conversation.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls Papa has not been her biological father ever since she could think.
Since the same areas of the brain are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, which also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected, such as Sarah K., to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "is taking place in the brain, the reality is reflected there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, so they seem so real."
Even nightly dream images value box as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
In contrast to schizophrenia, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Boundary state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our too conscious world, imaginary experiences are mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, Professor in Heidelberg and Chief Physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative – delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-like changed waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state afterwards.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self- and world loss, for example, by persistent, total incapacity to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of border state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is reflected in the imagination.
An intensive form of sense and meaning in an intrinsically unbearable situation, which enables us humans to not perish in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, while his body in the intensive care unit is doomed to motionlessness.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make drugs from blood.
When taken by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean Mafioso.
He goes up completely in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in the memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental journeys are still overly obvious to me after years and in minor details.
More clearly and more intensely than what was actually experienced.
The intensity of this experience is beyond the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of external reality are in the wake.
Every change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist Kasten sums up, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
