75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fruchtbarkeit und Karriere der Frauen in Spanien" conducted by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities on the labour market limited by their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether women work or not, and if so, what kind of profession they do.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the house, work only half-day or have no fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a permanent job, especially in the public sector, delay the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 years of age with a permanent employment are not given their first child, on average, until 3.7 years after they move together, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with a permanent employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have only completed the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a great influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar regarding the readiness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that needs to be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference has also been observed in women of the same age.
For example, women in the 35-49 age group became mothers for the first time, on average, at 25,1 or 32,1 for the first time, depending on whether they only have secondary education or higher education.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with their first graduation degree are already getting married and having their first child before their first appointment, the women with a middle or high school degree are doing it exactly the other way around and are first looking for a permanent position and getting married after it and then having their first child, Delgado notes.
