Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time, and as is currently the case with the ESP stability control system, the emergency braking systems must become compulsory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans; for the remaining vehicles, a waiting period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many rear-end accidents due to their working methods.
The task of the emergency brake assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the braking strength executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to a study commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not slowed down with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that one in four accidents could be prevented by personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assist exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
