CNMV has also announced that this offer is aimed at the acquisition of 550,008 shares of Federico Paternina at a price of EUR 7.65 per share, which in turn represents 8.95 % of the share capital consisting of EUR 6,142,786 in shares admitted to the Madrid and Bilbao stock exchanges.
It was also announced that 5,592,778 million shares have been fixed, which cannot be transferred in any way until the closing of the tender and whose price has been fixed by Federico Paternina in accordance with the law.
New programmes for the assessment of vehicles
In these days of storms and accidents not only the car workshops earn
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged to the workshops, where an expert must assess the damage and the cost of the repair.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes
That's why almost 100% of the reviewers use this type of system.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process them afterwards and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful programme.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all expert opinions are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing with the tool market for review and preparation of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is far from easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each providing the information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and motorizations have come on the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes onto the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because every single one of the thousands of vehicle parts must be catagolized and its price entered.
In addition, a "intelligent" graphic image is created by each model, on which you can "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, work can be completed in a week if the process is proceeding quickly.
If this is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, 99.2% of cars sold in Spain have complete information about Audatex.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the vehicle park on the roads, it is over 99%.
For the purpose of documenting and producing databases, Audatex has eight centres worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics experts) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive the updates every second day.
The development of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country there are also tools for the management of scrap parts or for the calculation of the value of a car.
The only company that informs about a guide who about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex offers this offer not in Spain, but in the United States.
When viewing the products that Audatex offers, it is easy to get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products AudaPlus, a standard solution for the assessment of accidents for the reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for according to the purpose, i.e. for each expert report.
It will be most expensive for customers who use it rarely, a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5,75 euros per month.
On the other hand, every insurance company that makes thousands of reports negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly line, using the chassis number alone.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle panes, and AudaSubastas is an open service on the Internet for the specialist market, with which one can offer for vehicles that have been declared as total damage.
Your statistics service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses or for obtaining information on the deviations by brand and model.
For example, it can be used to examine how many models of a particular brand had to go to the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a given period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes among others Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and supplies digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer in the same way.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa group, which was founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns or maintenance of vehicles.
The GT Expert Report Guide is a reference product on the market.
They work together with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 reviewers and 53 insurance companies.
Their business volume has increased to 20 % per year in the last three years and sales in 2008 amounted to 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year, they also began to go to the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its business is done in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, including 3,000 in Spain.
Total sales in the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) total 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2 % more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock market and today its shares are traded at a value of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, they have been on the New York Stock Exchange and part of the Standard & Poor's reference index.
Auctioning of accident cars on the Internet
Last October, the Solera Autoonline group bought a flatfom on the Internet for the sale of accident vehicles and motorcycles.
This purchase meant paying EUR 59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could increase to the remaining 15% next year.
The purpose of this purchase was to offer its customers more services and value added, with the possibility of gaining access to a huge international market.
This review and purchase service is exclusively aimed at industry professionals, such as insurance companies, reviewers, car rental companies, workshops, scrapyards and car dealers, who have to register before their activities.
This platform was founded in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations throughout Europe, 500,000 of them in Germany alone.
Its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The website now has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 reviewers.
Every day 3,000 ads are managed and 100 new ads are added to the Spanish market every day.
According to Spanish legislation, a vehicle whose chassis number has been deregistered may no longer drive on the roads, but certain non-damaged parts may be used as spare parts.
On the other hand, cars of historical value may be re-registered even if they have been unregistered after difficult administrative procedures.
Cost estimate of the workshop in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, the Audatex company ensures that the user receives a cost estimate in just four steps: identification of the vehicle, search of the spare part, creation and creation of a cost estimate.
The ease of use of these systems is a fundamental condition, especially in order to convince the older professionals, who are usually more or less opposed to the use of these new computer techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, 666 of which are passenger vehicles, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, you need a computer with internet connection for use.
After the model to be repaired has been identified by the chassis number, a graphic of the respective model appears and then the required spare part is selected.
The user can include variables such as the price of the working hours, surcharges or discounts, and after that he can print the estimate and pass it on to his customer.
However, AudaTaller is not a tool for peer review like AudaPlus, but rather a reference catalogue.
The main difference between the two systems is that the workshop oriented does not include estimated working hours.
The cost of using this tool is 350 euros a year, an amount that the customer can easily pay.
Currently, the company Audatex is working on offering these images in three-dimensional format.
This is an innovation that automechanics have been waiting for for a long time since, for example, they can be used to select a door and then turn the picture completely around to look at the inside.
